  "texts": [
    "Artificial intelligence ASPP Atrous spatial pyramid pooling B&W Black and white BBFID Bivalve and brachiopod fossil image dataset BIB/FIB-SEM Broad ion beam/Focused ion beam scanning electron microscopy CNN Convolutional neural network CT Computed tomography DCNN Deep convolutional neural network DL Deep learning DNN Deep neural network DSLR Deep learning based super resolution DWT Discrete wavelet transform EDX/EDS Energy dispersive X-ray/Energy dispersive spectroscopy ETDL Extended deep learning FM Fused model GAN Generative adversarial network GNN Graph neural network IF Infrared imaging IoU Intersection over union LSTM Long short-term memory MAE Mean absolute error MIC Minimum inhibitory values ML Machine learning MLP Multi-layer perceptron M1/M2 Model 1 and model 2 in hybrid modeling MPM Maximum projection model MSM Multislice model NIR Near infrared NLP Natural language processing NN Neural networks OM Optical microscopy OT Optical tomography PTME Permian-triassic mass extinction PRISMA Preferred reporting items for systematic reviews and meta-analyses PGGAN Progressively growing generative adversarial networks ReLU Rectified linear unit RGB Red-green-blue channel images RNN Recurrent neural network SE Squeeze-and-excitation blocks SEM Scanning electron microscopy SGD Stochastic gradient descent SL Supervised learning SME Substructure mask explanation SNP Single nucleotide polumorphism SS-CNN Semantic segmentation convolutional neural network SSIM Structural similarity index measure",
    "The study of ancient organisms through their preserved remains, including hard parts (e.g., bones, teeth, shells), and, in exceptional cases, soft tissues (Fabbri et al. 2020), alongside trace fossils that record the behaviour of these organisms, have been a cornerstone of paleontology for over 200 years.",
    "Indeed, since the dawn of modern paleontology, images of fossilized remains have been integral to the documentation and curation of faunal anatomy, facilitating the construction of phylogenetic trees of extinct groups, and the inference of paleoecologies of ancient organisms (Farris 1976; Morris 1979; Yang et al. 2016).",
    "Whilst traditionally taking the form of hand drawn biological illustrations, the emergence of multimodal digital imaging systems, such as scanning electron microscopy, (trinocular) optical microscopy, laser scanning confocal microscopy, X-ray computed tomography, automated serial sectioning, physical optical tomography, digital photography and structure from motion-multiview stereo photogrammetry have revolutionized the visual documentation of body fossils over the past several decades (Mehra and Maloof 2018; Garwood et al. 2009; Falkingham et al. 2011; Teaford 1988; Moutinho et al. 2016; Ball et al. 2016).",
    "These offer detailed insights into the morphology, and in the case of tomographic imaging, the internal structure of body fossils over a multitude of length-scales, from micro-organisms to the largest vertebrates known from the fossil record."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
